Headline::::
You are the Ref No363: Sergio Agüero




DateTime::::2016-03-04T09:30:30+0000



<p>Click to enlarge and debate the strip below the line.</p>

<p><strong>1) </strong>Goal. The only thing to be wary of is any potential gamesmanship from the injured player – but it seems pretty clear this wasn’t a deliberate attempt to impede an opponent. The defender should have done what he’s paid to do, and played to the whistle. Award the goal, and call on the physio. <em>Thanks to David Jones. </em><br/></p>

<p><strong>2) </strong>Nothing. The laws state that a player who removes his shirt “after scoring a goal” is cautioned for unsporting behaviour. There’s no reason to penalise this player: he can wear two identical layers if he’s cold, and he can take one off if that changes. If he left the field without permission to hand this shirt to a fan then that could pose a booking risk – but use some common sense. Get on with the game. <em>Thanks to James Stillman. </em><br/> <br/><strong>3)</strong> It’s a deliberate attempt to con you and cheat the opposition - but your hands are tied. You have to send him off and allow another player to take his kick. All you can hope is that when you report the facts after the game, the competition will do the right thing, intervene and award the result to the opposition. This is clearly an area where the laws need amending, to stop rewarding those who break them. We’ll see what emerges from the IFAB’s recent laws overhaul - but changes are proposed which should mean offending teams will no longer receive unfair benefit from their wrongdoing. <em>Bruce Nelson wins the shirt. </em></p>

